To create a TikZ diagram that visually represents the statement \(\mathbb{E}_{\mu_{\alpha, \beta_1}} [V(X)] < \mathbb{E}_{\mu_{\alpha, \beta_2}} [V(X)]\), we can use TikZ to draw two normal distributions with different means and standard deviations. Here's how you can do it:

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=10pt]{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric, arrows.meta}

\begin{document}

\tikzset{
    process/.style={rectangle, minimum width=3cm, minimum height=1cm, text centered, draw=black, fill=blue!30},
    arrow/.style={thick,->,>=stealth}
}

\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]

    % Define the first distribution
    \draw[domain=-5:5,samples=400] plot (\x,{1/sqrt(2*pi*0.5^2)*exp(-0.5*\x^2/0.5^2)}) node[right] {$\mu_{\alpha, \beta_1}$};

    % Define the second distribution
    \draw[domain=-5:5,samples=400] plot (\x,{1/sqrt(2*pi*1^2)*exp(-0.5*\x^2/1^2)}) node[right] at (6,0) {$\mu_{\alpha, \beta_2}$};

    % Draw the means
    \draw[dashed] (0,-0.1) -- (0,0.1);
    \draw[dashed] (6,-0.1) -- (6,0.1);

    % Label the means
    \node at (0,-0.3) {\(\mu_{\alpha, \beta_1}\)};
    \node at (6,-0.3) {\(\mu_{\alpha, \beta_2}\)};

    % Draw the inequality sign
    \node at (3,-1) {<};

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code will generate a TikZ diagram with two normal distributions side by side. The first distribution has a mean \(\mu_{\alpha, \beta_1}\)

